]]: [[Jon Huntsman, Jr.]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Vermont]]: [[Jim Douglas]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Governor of Virginia]]: [[Mark Warner]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 14), [[Tim Kaine]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (starting January 14)\n* [[Governor of Washington]]: [[Christine Gregoire]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of West Virginia]]: [[Joe Manchin]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Governor of Wisconsin]]: [[Jim Doyle]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Governor of Wyoming]]: [[Dave Freudenthal]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n}}\n\n=== Lieutenant governors ===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Alabama]]: [[Lucy Baxley]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Alaska]]: [[Loren Leman]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until December 4), [[Sean Parnell]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting December 4)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Arkansas]]: [[Winthrop Paul Rockefeller]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until July 16), vacant (starting July 16)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of California]]: [[Cruz Bustamante]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Colorado]]: [[Jane E. Norton]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Connecticut]]: [[Kevin Sullivan (politician)|Kevin B. Sullivan]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Delaware]]: [[John Carney (politician)|John Carney]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Florida]]: [[Toni Jennings]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Georgia]]: [[Mark Taylor (American politician)|Mark Taylor]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Hawaii]]: [[Duke Aiona]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Idaho]]: \n** until May 26: [[Jim Risch]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n** May 26-June 15: vacant\n** starting June 15: [[Mark Ricks]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Illinois]]: [[Pat Quinn (politician)|Pat Quinn]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Indiana]]: [[Becky Skillman]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Iowa]]: [[Sally Pederson]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Kansas]]: [[John E. Moore]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Kentucky]]: [[Steve Pence]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Louisiana]]: [[Mitch Landrieu]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Maryland]]: [[Michael Steele]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Massachusetts]]: [[Kerry Healey]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Michigan]]: [[John D. Cherry]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Minnesota]]: [[Carol Molnau]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Mississippi]]: [[Amy Tuck]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Missouri]]: [[Peter Kinder]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Montana]]: [[John Bohlinger]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Nebraska]]: [[Rick Sheehy]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Nevada]]: [[Lorraine Hunt]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of New Mexico]]: [[Diane Denish]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of New York]]: [[Mary Donohue]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until end of December 31)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of North Carolina]]: [[Bev Perdue]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of North Dakota]]: [[Jack Dalrymple]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Ohio]]: [[Bruce E. Johnson]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (until December 8), vacant (starting December 8)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Oklahoma]]: [[Mary Fallin]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Pennsylvania]]: [[Catherine Baker Knoll]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Rhode Island]]: [[Charles J. Fogarty]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of South Carolina]]: [[Andr\u00e9 Bauer]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of South Dakota]]: [[Dennis Daugaard]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Tennessee]]: [[John S. Wilder]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Texas]]: [[David Dewhurst]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Utah]]: [[Gary Herbert]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Vermont]]: [[Brian Dubie]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Virginia]]: [[Tim Kaine]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) (until January 14), [[Bill Bolling]] ([[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]) (starting January 14)\n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Washington]]: [[Brad Owen]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]) \n* [[Lieutenant Governor of Wisconsin]]: [[Barbara Lawton]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]])\n}}\n|}\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== January ===\n[[File:NASA TV - New Horizons Pluto Launch (January 19, 2006).ogg|thumb|right|[[January 19]]: ''[[New Horizons]]'' probe launched from [[Cape Canaveral Air Force Station|Cape Canaveral]].]]\n[[File:Ben Bernanke official portrait.jpg|thumb|120px|[[January 30]]: [[Ben Bernanke]] 14th [[Chairman of the Federal Reserve]]]]\n* [[January 2]]\n** The annual [[Rose Parade]] in [[California]] is drenched in heavy rain for the first time in 51 years.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/03/national/03storm.html?scp=1&sq=&st=nyt|title=Flowers Remain Bright as Rare Rain Falls on the Rose Parade|work = [[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 3, 2006 | first=Cindy | last=Chang| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225957/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/03/national/03storm.html?scp=1&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n** [[Pepsico]] announces its purchase of Star Foods for an undisclosed price saying that the purchase would strengthen its place as [[Poland]]'s number one seller of [[potato chip]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/03/business/03pepsi.html?scp=10&sq=&st=nyt|title=PepsiCo Buys Star Foods|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 3, 2006 | work=The New York Times| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225741/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/03/business/03pepsi.html?scp=10&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 3]] &ndash; Twelve dead coal miners and one survivor are discovered in the [[Sago Mine disaster|Sago Mine Disaster]] near [[Buckhannon, West Virginia]].\n* [[January 5]]\n** The [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]] proposes spending [[United States dollar|$]]114 million on educational programs to expand the teaching of [[Arabic]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Persian language|Persian]] and other languages typically not taught in public schools.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/06/politics/06language.html?scp=1&sq=&st=nyt|title=Bush Proposes Broader Language Training|work=The New York Times|date=January 6, 2006|accessdate=2009-03-20 | first=Michael | last=Janofsky| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225914/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/06/politics/06language.html?scp=1&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n** [[IBM]] says that it would freeze pension benefits for its American employees starting in 2008 and offer them only a [[401k]] retirement plan in future.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/06/business/06pension.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt|title=I.B.M. to Freeze Pension Plans to Trim Costs|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 6, 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225836/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/06/business/06pension.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 6]]\n** [[AOL]] agrees to pay customers as much as [[United States dollar|$]]25 million to settle claims that it wrongly billed them for some online services and products.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/07/technology/07aol.html?scp=10&sq=&st=nyt|title=AOL to Settle Billing Complaints|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 7, 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225944/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/07/technology/07aol.html?scp=10&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n** [[NYSE]] says that it has picked [[Bear Wagner]] as the firm that will handle trading of its shares when it goes public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/07/business/07firm.html?scp=8&sq=&st=nyt|title=Big Board Selects Trader for Its Shares|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 7, 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424230020/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/07/business/07firm.html?scp=8&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 7]] &ndash; Embroiled in multiple scandals, former U.S. [[House Majority Leader]] [[Tom DeLay]] announces he will not seek to reassume his former post.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/01/07/AR2006010700831_pf.html|title=After Tom DeLay|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2006-02-08|accessdate=2009-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/delay-drops-bid-to-return-as-majority-leader|title=DeLay steps down as majority leader|publisher=[[MarketWatch]]|last=Watts|first= William L.|author2=Gelsi, Steve|date=2006-01-07|accessdate=2009-07-05}}</ref>\n* [[January 9]]\n**[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Dick Cheney]] complains of [[shortness of breath]] and is treated at the hospital. The [[White House]] says the trip was necessary because of fluid retention as a [[adverse effect|side effect]] of a drug Mr. Cheney had taken to treat chronic foot ailments.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/10/politics/10cheney.html?scp=10&sq=&st=nyt|title=Cheney Makes a Morning Trip to the Hospital|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 10, 2006 | first1=David E. | last1=Sanger | first2=Lawrence K. | last2=Altman| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225951/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/10/politics/10cheney.html?scp=10&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n** The [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] closes above 11,000 (11,011.90) for the first time since June 7, 2001.\n* [[January 10]] &ndash; [[Governor of California|Governor]] [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] proposes a [[United States dollar|$]]125.6 billion budget increasing spending without raising taxes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/11/national/11arnold.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt|title=Schwarzenegger Budget Calls for Billions in New Spending|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 11, 2006 | first=John M. | last=Broder| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225849/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/11/national/11arnold.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 11]] &ndash; The [[Augustine Volcano]] in [[Alaska]] erupts twice, marking its first major eruption since 1986.\n* [[January 13]]\n** The [[US Government]] reports that [[wholesale price index|wholesale]] inflation in 2005 increased by highest amount since 1990.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/14/business/14econ.html?scp=9&sq=&st=nyt|title=Wholesale Inflation Increases by Highest Amount Since 1990|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 14, 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225936/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/14/business/14econ.html?scp=9&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n** [[Rick Wagoner]], [[CEO]] of the loss-making [[General Motors]] says that results will improve in 2006 and 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/14/business/14auto.html?scp=24&sq=&st=nyt|title=G.M. Chief Says Results Will Improve|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 14, 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424230052/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/14/business/14auto.html?scp=24&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 15]] &ndash; [[NASA]]'s [[Stardust (spacecraft)|Stardust]] mission successfully ends, the first to return dust from a [[comet]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,181763,00.html|title=Stardust Container in Almost Perfect Condition|date=2006-01-17|accessdate=2009-07-06|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181106160304/https://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,181763,00.html|archive-date=2018-11-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[January 17]] &ndash; [[California]] executes [[Clarence Ray Allen]] (death by [[lethal injection]]), who was sentenced to death in 1982 for arranging the murders of three people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/18/national/18execute.html?scp=15&sq=&st=nyt|title=California Executes 76-Year-Old in Murders of 3 People|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 18, 2006 | first=Randal C. | last=Archibold| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225755/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/18/national/18execute.html?scp=15&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 18]] &ndash; [[American International Group]], the world's largest insurer, says that its [[chief operating officer]] [[Donald P. Kanak]] has resigned and stepped down from the board \"for personal reasons\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E07E1D9153FF93AA25752C0A9609C8B63&scp=8&sq=&st=nyt|title=A.I.G.'s Operating Chief Steps Down; 2 Directors Are Named|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 19, 2006}}</ref>\n* [[January 19]] &ndash; [[NASA]] launches the ''[[New Horizons]]'' spacecraft in a 9-year, 3 billion mile space mission, to flyby and observe the dwarf planetary system of [[Pluto]]/[[Charon (moon)|Charon]] and possibly other [[Kuiper belt objects]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/20/science/space/20pluto.html?scp=8&sq=&st=nyt|title=NASA Launches Spacecraft on the First Mission to Pluto|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 20, 2006 | first=Warren E. | last=Leary| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424230028/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/20/science/space/20pluto.html?scp=8&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 20]] &ndash; A [[Maryland]] judge strikes down a state law banning [[same-sex marriage]] saying the measure violated a state constitutional amendment prohibiting sex discrimination.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/21/national/21marriage.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt|title=Maryland Judge Voids Ban on Same-Sex Marriage; State Quickly Appeals|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 21, 2006 | first=Adam | last=Liptak| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424230038/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/21/national/21marriage.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 26]] &ndash; [[General Motors]] reports an [[United States dollar|$]]8.6 billion loss for 2005, its biggest loss since 1992.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/27/business/27auto.html?scp=11&sq=&st=nyt|title=G.M. Posts Worst Loss Since 1992|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 27, 2006 | first=Micheline | last=Maynard| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225828/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/27/business/27auto.html?scp=11&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 27]] &ndash; An inhaled form of [[insulin]] wins federal approval offering an alternative to [[Injection (medicine)|injection]]s for millions of people with [[diabetes]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/28/health/28diabetes.html?scp=4&sq=&st=nyt|title=U.S. Regulators Approve Insulin in Inhaled Form|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 28, 2006 | first1=Andrew | last1=Pollack | first2=Alex | last2=Berenson| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225841/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/28/health/28diabetes.html?scp=4&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 30]]\n**The [[White House]] announces that [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush|Bush]] has chosen Professor [[Edward Lazear]], a [[Stanford University]] business professor to succeed [[Ben Bernanke]] as chairman of his [[Council of Economic Advisors]] who will succeed [[Alan Greenspan]] as Chairman of the [[Federal Reserve]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E06E4D81E3FF932A05752C0A9609C8B63&scp=15&sq=&st=nyt|title=White House Aide Picked|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-21|date=January 31, 2006}}</ref>\n** [[Jennifer San Marco]] kills eight people before committing suicide at a postal facility in [[Goleta, California]]. San Marco had worked at the facility previously, but had been let go due to her erratic behavior.\n* [[January 31]]\n** [[Samuel Alito]] is sworn in as an associate justice of the [[Supreme Court of the United States]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,183442,00.html|title=The Confirmation of Samuel Alito to the Supreme Court|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company]]|date=2006-02-01|accessdate=2009-07-06|first=Bill|last=O'Reilly}}</ref>\n** Two [[federal appeals court]]s uphold rulings that the [[Partial Birth Abortion Act]] passed by the [[United States Congress]] in 2003 is [[Constitution of the United States|unconstitutional]] because it does not include an exception when the health of a pregnant woman is at risk.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/01/politics/01abortion.html?scp=12&sq=&st=nyt|title=Partial Birth Abortion Act Ruled Unconstitutional by U.S. Courts|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-21|date=February 1, 2006 | first=Julia | last=Preston| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424230006/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/01/politics/01abortion.html?scp=12&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n=== February ===\n[[Image:Euphronios krater side A MET L.2006.10.jpg|thumb|right|120px|[[February 2]]: [[Euphronios krater]].]]\n[[Image:ApoloOhno.jpg|thumb|right|120px|[[February 10]] &ndash; [[February 26]]: Gold medalist [[Apolo Ohno]] at the [[Short track speed skating at the 2006 Winter Olympics|Men's 500&nbsp;meters medal ceremony]].]]\n* [[February 1]] &ndash; [[UAL Corporation]], [[United Airlines]]' parent company, emerges from bankruptcy after being in that position since December 9, 2002, the longest such filing in history.\n* [[February 2]] &ndash; After over 30 years, the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] says it would relinquish ownership of a 2,500-year-old Greek vase, the [[Euphronios krater]], to Italy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/03/arts/03muse.html?scp=1&sq=&st=nyt|title=The Met, Ending 30-Year Stance, Is Set to Yield Prized Vase to Italy|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=February 3, 2006 | first1=Randy | last1=Kennedy | first2=Hugh | last2=Eakin| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225929/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/03/arts/03muse.html?scp=1&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[February 3]] &ndash; Suspicious fires destroy three small churches and damage two others in [[Bibb County, Alabama|Bibb County]], [[Alabama]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/04/national/04churches.html?scp=1&sq=&st=nyt|title=Fires Destroy 3 Churches and Damage 2 in Alabama|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-21|date=February 4, 2006 | first1=Jim | last1=Noles | first2=Campbell | last2=Robertson| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225806/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/04/national/04churches.html?scp=1&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[February 5]] &ndash; [[Super Bowl XL]]: The [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] defeat the [[Seattle Seahawks]] by a score of 21&ndash;10. It is a homecoming for [[Detroit]] native [[Jerome Bettis]], who was playing the final game of his 12-year career.\n* [[February 9]] &ndash; [[AIG]] apologizes for deceptive business practices and reaches a [[United States dollar|$]]1.64 billion settlement with federal and state securities and insurance regulators.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/10/business/10insure.html?scp=21&sq=&st=nyt|title=A.I.G. Apologizes and Agrees to $1.64 Billion Settlement|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-21|date=February 10, 2006 | first=Gretchen | last=Morgenson| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424230001/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/10/business/10insure.html?scp=21&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[February 10]]&ndash;[[February 26]] &ndash; The [[United States at the 2006 Winter Olympics|United States]] compete at the [[2006 Winter Olympics|Winter Olympics]] in [[Turin]], [[Italy]] and win 9 gold, 9 silver, and 7 bronze medals.{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n* [[February 11]] &ndash; Vice President [[Dick Cheney]] [[Dick Cheney hunting incident|accidentally shoots and wounds a lawyer]] while quail hunting in southern [[Texas]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/13/politics/13cheney.html?scp=2&sq=&st=nyt|title=Cheney Shoots Fellow Hunter in Mishap on a Texas Ranch|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-22|date=February 13, 2006 | first=Anne E. | last=Kornblut| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424230017/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/13/politics/13cheney.html?scp=2&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[February 14]] &ndash; [[The Coca-Cola Company]] says that [[Warren Buffett]], the soft drink maker's largest shareholder, would leave the board in April after 19 years in order to spend more time managing [[Berkshire Hathaway]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/15/business/15coke.html?scp=22&sq=&st=nyt|title=After 17 Years, Buffett to Exit Coke's Board|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-28|date=February 15, 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424230034/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/15/business/15coke.html?scp=22&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[February 15]] &ndash; A group of institutional investors already involved in a lawsuit with the company sue [[Tyco International]] to stop its proposed breakup plan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/16/business/16tyco.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt|title=Investors Sue Tyco Over Proposed Breakup|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-28|date=February 16, 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225933/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/16/business/16tyco.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[February 16]]\n** The state of [[Minnesota]] sues [[AIG]] for underreporting premiums to reduce its tax bill refusing a settlement of [[United States dollar|$]]1.2 million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E03EEDD103EF934A25751C0A9609C8B63&scp=5&sq=&st=nyt|title=Minnesota Sues A.I.G.|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-28|date=February 17, 2006}}</ref>\n** The chairman of the [[Federal Reserve]], [[Ben Bernanke]], testifies to the US Senate that Chinese ownership of US assets is not large enough to put the country at risk economically.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/17/business/worldbusiness/17fed.html?scp=6&sq=&st=nyt|title=U.S. Assets Safe in China, Fed Chief Says|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-28|date=February 17, 2006}}</ref>\n** The [[Department of Commerce]] reports that housing starts jumped 14.5% to a 33&ndash;year high in January.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/17/business/17econ.html?scp=13&sq=&st=nyt|title=Housing Starts in January Hit 33-Year High|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-28|date=February 17, 2006 | first=Vikas | last=Bajaj| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225824/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/17/business/17econ.html?scp=13&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n=== March ===\n[[File:BB61 USS Iowa BB61 broadside USN.jpg|thumb|120px|[[March 17]]: {{sclass-|Iowa|battleship}}]]\n* [[March 2]] &ndash; The colorized [[United States ten-dollar bill|$10 bill]] is released, with the same color-shifting ink and security features of the $20 and $50 bills that preceded it.\n* [[March 4]] &ndash; The final contact attempt with [[Pioneer 10]] receives no response.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetary.org/blog/article/00000477/ |title=The final attempt to contact Pioneer 10 |date=2006-03-06 |accessdate=2009-07-06 |publisher=[[The Planetary Society]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605084332/http://www.planetary.org/blog/article/00000477/ |archivedate=2011-06-05 }}</ref>\n* [[March 6]]&ndash;[[March 20]] &ndash; The first [[World Baseball Classic]] is held in [[San Diego]], [[California]].\n* [[March 9]] &ndash; [[NASA]]'s [[Cassini-Huygens]] spacecraft discovers [[geysers]] of a liquid substance shooting from [[Saturn]]'s moon [[Enceladus (moon)|Enceladus]], signaling a possible presence of water.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2006/03/0310_060310_saturn.html?source=rss|title=Saturn Moon Has Water Geysers and, Just Maybe, Life|publisher=[[National Geographic Society]]|date=2006-03-10|accessdate=2009-07-06|first=Elizabeth|last=Svoboda}}</ref>\n* [[March 10]] &ndash; NASA's [[Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter]] enters Mars orbit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/TECH/space/03/09/mars.orbiter.preview/index.html|title=Payoff high in risky Mars mission|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=2006-03-10|accessdate=2009-07-06|first=Peggy|last=Mihelich}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2006/03/0310_060310_mars_orbit.html|title=Mars's Gravity Captures NASA Spacecraft|publisher=[[National Geographic Society]]|date=2006-03-10|first=John|last=Roach| accessdate= 30 October 2009 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n* [[March 14]] &ndash; [[Crystal Mangum]] makes false rape accusations against three members of the Duke University men's lacrosse team, an event which marked the beginning of the [[Duke lacrosse case]]<ref>{{Cite book | url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=l-Cm2gE7gYsC | title=Until Proven Innocent: Political Correctness and the Shameful Injustices of the Duke Lacrosse Rape Case| isbn=9781429961097| last1=Stuart Taylor| first1=Jr| last2=Gray| first2=Patrick| date=April 2010}}</ref>\n* [[March 16]] &ndash; The [[Blu-ray Disc]] format is released in the United States.\n* [[March 17]] &ndash; The United States strikes its 2 remaining {{sclass-|Iowa|battleship}}s from the [[Naval Vessel Register]], ending the age of the battleship.\n* [[March 22]] &ndash; The [[Federal Reserve]] stops the publishing of M3 money supply data.\n* [[March 25]] &ndash; Seven die in the [[Capitol Hill Massacre]] in [[Seattle]], Washington. Perpetrator Kyle Huff's rampage is fueled by his hatred of \"rave scene\" gatherings.\n\n=== April ===\n* [[April 4]] &ndash; First material action in [[2006 Minor League Baseball umpire strike|Minor League Baseball umpire strike]].\n* [[April 29]] &ndash; Massive anti-war demonstrations and a march down [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] in [[New York City]] mark the third year of [[Iraq War|war in Iraq]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2008}}\n\n=== May ===\n* [[May 1]] &ndash; The [[Great American Boycott]] takes place across the United States as marchers protest for immigration rights.\n* [[May 5]] &ndash; [[Fiat]] chairman [[Sergio Marchionne]] announces that the [[Alfa Romeo]] automobile brand will return to the United States in 2008, after a 13-year hiatus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mobilemag.com/2006/05/05/alfa-romeo-coming-back-to-the-us/ |title=Alfa Romeo coming back to the U.S. |first=T.O. |last=Whenham |date=2006-05-05 |accessdate=2009-07-21 |publisher=[[Mobile Magazine]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5iUG4kH3v?url=http://www.mobilemag.com/2006/05/05/alfa-romeo-coming-back-to-the-us/ |archivedate=2009-07-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== June ===\n* [[June 7]] &ndash; [[Al-Qaeda in Iraq]] leader [[Abu Musab al-Zarqawi]] and seven of his aides are killed in a U.S. air raid just north of the town of [[Baquba]], [[Iraq]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,198651,00.html|title=Abu Musab al-Zarqawi Killed in Bombing Raid|publisher=[[The Associated Press]]|date=2006-06-08|accessdate=2009-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,198657,00.html|title=Bush: 'Zarqawi Has Met His End'|first=Liza|last=Porteus|author2=Turner, Trish |author3=Baier, Bret|publisher=[[Fox News Channel|Fox News]]|date=2006-06-08|accessdate=2009-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://fr.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1149572640723&pagename=JPost/JPArticle/ShowFull |title=US airstrike kills Abu Musab al-Zarqawi |publisher=[[Jerusalem Post]] |date=2006-06-08 |accessdate=2009-07-25 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5iaprQi5j?url=http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1149572640723&pagename=JPost%2FJPArticle%2FShowFull |archivedate=2009-07-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*[[June 12]] &ndash; [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] [[quarterback]] [[Ben Roethlisberger]] crashes his motorcycle near [[Pittsburgh|Pittsburgh's]] 10th Street bridge. He is rushed to [[UPMC Mercy|Mercy Hospital]] for emergency surgery.\n*[[June 19]] &ndash; The Carolina Hurricanes defeat the Edmonton Oilers 2-1 in game 7 of the 2006 Stanley Cup Finals to give the Hurricanes their first Stanley Cup in franchise history. It is also the first Stanley Cup Finals since the [[2004\u201305 NHL lockout|2004-05 lockout]] that cancelled all games that year.\n* [[June 23]] &ndash; In [[Miami]], the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] arrests seven men, accusing them of planning to bomb the [[Sears Tower]] and other attacks in Miami.\n* [[June 25]] &ndash; [[Warren Buffett]] donates over [[United States dollar|$]]30 billion to the [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]].\n\n=== July ===\n* [[July 4]] &ndash; [[STS-121|STS&ndash;121]]: [[Space Shuttle Discovery|Space Shuttle ''Discovery'']] is launched to the [[International Space Station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.space.com/missionlaunches/060704_sts121_spaceshot.html |title=Shuttle Discovery Reaches Orbit |publisher=[[The Associated Press]] |first=Tariq |last=Malik |date=2006-07-04 |accessdate=2009-08-05 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5ix2x7gLa?url=http://www.space.com/missionlaunches/060704_sts121_spaceshot.html |archivedate=2009-08-11 |url-status=live }}</ref> It returns safely on July 17. It is the second \"return to flight\" mission after the [[Space Shuttle Columbia disaster|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'' disaster]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.space.com/missionlaunches/060717_discovery_return.html|title=Landing Day: Space Shuttle Discovery Returns to Earth|publisher=[[Space.com]]|first=Tariq|last=Malik|date=2006-07-17|accessdate=2009-08-05}}</ref>\n* [[July 5]] &ndash; [[North Korea]] [[2006 North Korean missile test|test fires]] missiles, timed with the liftoff of [[Space Shuttle Discovery|Space Shuttle ''Discovery'']], preceding the fireworks celebrations that night in America. The long range [[Taepodong-2|Taepodong&ndash;2]] reportedly fails shortly after takeoff.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=awuAN4B9yYSs|title=North Korea Launches Taepodong-2 Missile: Timeline (Update2)|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]]|date=2006-07-05|accessdate=2009-08-05}}</ref>\n* [[July 10]] &ndash; [[Henry Paulson]] is sworn in as the new [[United States Secretary of Treasury|Secretary of Treasury]], succeeding [[John W. Snow]].{{citation needed|date=February 2013}}\n\n=== August ===\n[[Image:TSA Service Monkey.jpg|thumb|right|120px|[[August 10]]: A United States [[Transportation Security Administration|TSA]] agent inspects a service monkey before a flight.]]\n* [[August 10]] &ndash; [[Metropolitan Police Service|London Metropolitan Police]] make 21 arrests in connection to an apparent [[2006 transatlantic aircraft plot|terrorist plot]] that involved aircraft traveling from the [[United Kingdom]] to the United States. Liquids and gels are banned from checked and carry-on baggage.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,207710,00.html|title=Bush Praises Effort to Thwart Terror Plot|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|accessdate=2009-10-09|date=2006-08-10|first=Sharon Kehnemui|last=Liss}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2006-08/30/content_5029706.htm|title=Three \"UK air plot\" suspects remanded|publisher=[[Xinhua News Agency]]|accessdate=2009-10-10|date=2006-08-30|first=Mo|last=Honge}}</ref> As of September 26, the [[Transportation Security Administration]] adjusts its ban on liquids, aerosols and gels. Travelers are permitted to carry liquids through security checkpoints in containers of 3.4&nbsp;ounces (100&nbsp;mL) or less that fit comfortably in one quart-size clear plastic zip-top bag. This procedure came to be known as \"3-1-1 for carry-ons\" (3.4&nbsp;ounce containers in a 1 quart bag, 1 bag per passenger). Items purchased in the airside zone after clearing security could be brought on board without restriction. Other exemptions to this restriction include medications and breast milk.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tsa.gov/travelers/airtravel/prohibited/permitted-prohibited-items.shtm |title=Prohibited Items For Travelers |publisher=[[Transportation Security Administration]] |accessdate=19 February 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090225064012/http://www.tsa.gov/travelers/airtravel/prohibited/permitted-prohibited-items.shtm| archivedate=February 25, 2009| url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[August 27]] &ndash; [[Comair Flight 5191]], carrying 50 people, crashes shortly after takeoff from [[Blue Grass Airport]] in [[Lexington, Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/thestar/access/1110297431.html?dids=1110297431:1110297431&FMT=ABS&FMTS|title=49 dead in fiery Kentucky crash; Pilot took off from the wrong runway 2 Canadians killed, co-pilot survives|publisher=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=2009-10-10|date=2006-08-28}}</ref>\n* [[August 28]] &ndash; A [[Greyhound Lines]] bus from [[New York City]] to [[Montreal]], carrying 52 people, crashes at mile 115 on [[Interstate 87 (New York)|I&ndash;87]] near [[Elizabethtown, New York|Elizabethtown]], killing five people, including the driver, and seriously injuring others.\n* [[August 29]] &ndash; The United States commemorates the first anniversary of the [[Hurricane Katrina]].\n\n=== September ===\n* [[Septembewash]]; [[Gordon B. Hinckley]] dedicates the [[Sacramento California Temple]], the LDS Church's seventh temple in California.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ldschurchnewsarchive.com/temples/97/Sacramento-California.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140513184321/http://www.ldschurchnewsarchive.com/temples/97/Sacramento-California.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=May 13, 2014 |work=LDS Church News |title=Sacramento California Temple |accessdate=December 21, 2016}}</ref>\n*[[September 4]] &ndash; While filming ''[[Ocean's Deadliest]]'', television host [[Steve Irwin]] is stung by a [[Stingray|sting ray]] and killed off the coast of [[Australia]].\n* [[September 8]] &ndash; The world's tallest living tree, a {{convert|115.61|m|ft}} tall [[Sequoia sempervirens|coast redwood]] (sequoia) now named \"[[Hyperion (tree)|Hyperion]]\", is discovered in [[Redwood National and State Parks|Redwood National Park]].\n* [[September 11]] &ndash; The United States commemorates the fifth anniversary of the [[September 11 attacks|9/11 attacks]] in [[New York City]].\n* [[September 15]] &ndash; [[2006 United States E. coli outbreak|Spinach contaminated with E. coli]] kills two and poisons over 100 others in 20 states.\n*[[September 24]]- The [[New Orleans Saints]] play their first game at the [[Mercedes-Benz Superdome|Superdome]] since Hurricane Katrina with a 23-3 victory over [[Falcons\u2013Saints rivalry|NFC South rival]] [[Atlanta Falcons]].\n\n=== October ===\n* October &ndash; The unemployment rate drops to 4.4%, the lowest since May 2001.\n* [[October 2]] &ndash; [[Charles Carl Roberts IV]], a 32-yr-old milk-truck driver, [[West Nickel Mines School shooting|kills 5 girls]] at an [[Amish]] schoolhouse in Lancaster County, Pennsylvania before shooting himself.\n* [[October 3]] &ndash; The [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] gains 56.99 points, or 0.49 percent, with a close of 11,727.34, its first all-time high in more than 6 years after it last hit in a record high of 11,722.98 on January 20, 2000.\n* [[October 6]] &ndash; A hazardous waste plant near [[Apex, North Carolina]] explodes, releasing chlorine gas, and resulting in the evacuation of thousands and the hospitalization of over 200 residents.\n* [[October 10]] &ndash; [[Google]] buys [[YouTube]] for [[United States dollar|$]]1.65 billion.\n* [[October 11]] &ndash; A plane [[2006 New York City plane crash|crashes]] into a highrise building New York City, killing two.\n* [[October 12]] &ndash; [[Lake Storm \"Aphid\"]]: A freak snowstorm blows into [[Buffalo, New York]], leaving over 400,000 without power and killing 13.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wpvi/story?section=news/national_world&id=4654481|title=Snow Arrives in Buffalo|publisher=[[The Associated Press]]|date=2006-10-12|accessdate=2009-10-11}}</ref>\n* [[October 16]] &ndash; The last American [[Mobile Army Surgical Hospital|MASH]] is [[Demobilization|decommissioned]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.military.com/features/0,15240,117360,00.html|title=Army's Last MASH Becomes a CSH|publisher=[[Military.com]]|first=Christine|last=June|accessdate=2009-10-11|date=2006-10-20}}</ref>\n* [[October 19]] &ndash; The [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] closes 12,000 for the first time, 12,011.73.\n* [[October 24]] &ndash; [[NASA]]'s [[MESSENGER]] spacecraft makes its first flyby of [[Venus]] (it will be captured into Mercury's orbit on March 18, 2011).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planetary.org/news/2006/1024_MESSENGER_Swings_By_Venus_on_its_Way_to.html|title=MESSENGER Swings By Venus on its Way to Mercury|publisher=Planetory|accessdate=2009-10-11|date=2006-10-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090803053732/http://www.planetary.org/news/2006/1024_MESSENGER_Swings_By_Venus_on_its_Way_to.html|archive-date=2009-08-03|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[October 27]] &ndash; The [[St. Louis Cardinals]] defeat the [[Detroit Tigers]] to win their 10th world series.\n\n=== November ===\n* [[November 6]] &ndash; [[United States elections, 2006|Mid-term elections]] result in the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] gaining control of both houses of [[United States Congress|Congress]].\n* [[November 19]] &ndash; Nintendo's [[Wii]] released in America.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Nintendo Wii offers a new way to play video games - Nov. 15, 2006|url=http://money.cnn.com/2006/11/15/commentary/wii_review/index.htm|accessdate=3 September 2016|date=15 November 2006|website=CNN Money|last=Morris|first=Chris}}</ref>\n\n=== December ===\n\n* [[December 7]] &ndash; Smoking is banned in all [[Ohio]] bars, restaurants, workplaces, and other public places.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-28850840_ITM|date=2006-12-07|publisher=[[The Columbus Dispatch]]|title=Smoking ban in effect, but penalties in limbo.|accessdate=2009-10-12|author1=Mark Ferenchik  |author2=James Nash}}</ref>\n* [[December 10]] &ndash; Space Shuttle Mission [[STS-116|STS&ndash;116]]: [[Space Shuttle Discovery|Space Shuttle ''Discovery'']] lifts off from the [[Kennedy Space Center]] on the first night launch since the 2003 [[Space Shuttle Columbia disaster|loss of ''Columbia'']].\n* [[December 13]] &ndash; U.S. Senator [[Tim Johnson (U.S. Senator)|Tim Johnson]] ([[Democratic Party (United States)|D]]&ndash;South Dakota) suffers a [[brain hemorrhage]] during a conference call with reporters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/2007-09-05-johnson-return_N.htm |title=Sen. Johnson welcomed back to work |date=September 5, 2007 |last=Bremner |first=Faith |newspaper=[[USA Today]]| accessdate= 12 September 2010 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n* [[December 14]] &ndash; The U.S. [[spy satellite]] [[USA-193|USA&ndash;193]], also known as NRO Launch 21 (NROL&ndash;21 or simply L&ndash;21), is launched but malfunctions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=2006-057A|title=USA 193 data|publisher=[[NASA]]|accessdate=2009-10-13 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n* [[December 15]] &ndash; [[Lockheed Martin]]'s [[F-35 Lightning II|F&ndash;35 Lightning II]] Joint Strike Fighter successfully flies for the first time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/wires/2006Dec15/0,4670,JointStrikeFighter,00.html|title=F-35 Test Flight Deemed a Success|publisher=[[The Associated Press]]|accessdate=2009-10-13|date=2006-12-16|first=Angela K|last=Brown}}</ref>\n* [[December 18]] &ndash; [[Robert Gates]] is sworn in as the new [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]], succeeding [[Donald Rumsfeld]].<ref name=\"sworn in\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/6190279.stm |title=New US defence secretary sworn in |work=BBC News |date=December 18, 2006|accessdate=December 18, 2006}}</ref>\n* [[December 22]] &ndash; The Space Shuttle ''Discovery'' lands at the Kennedy Space Center, concluding a 2&ndash;week mission to the [[International Space Station]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601103&sid=a1VtwOnkxyqE&refer=us|title=Shuttle Discovery Touches Down Safely at Kennedy Space Center|accessdate=2009-10-13|date=2006-12-22|first=Demian|last=McLean|publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.|Bloomberg]]}}</ref>\n* [[December 26]] &ndash; Former President [[Gerald Ford]] dies at the age of 93 in [[Rancho Mirage, California|Rancho Mirage]], [[California]].\n\n=== Undated ===\n* [[United States housing bubble]]: A total of 1,259,118 foreclosures are filed during 2006, up 42 percent from 2005.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.realtytrac.com/content/press-releases/more-than-12-million-foreclosure-filings-reported-in-2006-2234 |work=[[RealtyTrac]] |title=More than 1.2 million foreclosure filings reported in 2006 |date=2007-01-25 |accessdate=12 September 2010  |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20100907043129/http://www.realtytrac.com/content/press-releases/more-than-12-million-foreclosure-filings-reported-in-2006-2234 |archivedate=2010-09-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Subprime mortgage crisis]]: The housing bubble burst in the summer of 2006, starting a chain of events that would eventually develop into a full-blown market meltdown.\n\n=== Ongoing ===\n* [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]] (2001\u2013present)\n* [[Iraq War]] (2003\u20132011)\n\n==Births==\n* January 3 George w bush\n* [[April 8]] &ndash; Moses Bruce Anthony Martin, son of [[Chris Martin]] and [[Gwyneth Paltrow]]\n* [[April 18]] &ndash; Suri Cruise, daughter of [[Tom Cruise]] and [[Katie Holmes]]\n* [[May 6]] &ndash; Sadie Sandler, actress and daughter of [[Adam Sandler]]\n* [[September 7]] &ndash; Dannielynn Marshall Birkhead, notable paternity case subject and daughter of [[Anna Nicole Smith]]\n\n== [[:Category:2006 deaths|Deaths]] ==\n\n=== [[Deaths in January 2006|January]] ===\n<!--[[File:Lou rawls edit.png|120px|thumb|[[Lou Rawls]]]]-->\n[[File:Studio publicity Shelley Winters.jpg|120px|thumb|[[Shelley Winters]]]]\n[[File:Tony Franciosa - 1969.jpg|120px|thumb|[[Anthony Franciosa]]]]\n[[File:Coretta Scott King.jpg|120px|thumb|[[Coretta Scott King]]]]\n* [[January 1]]\n** [[Harry Magdoff]], economist, (b. [[1913 in the United States|1913]])\n** [[Gideon Rodan]], Romanian-born American physician (b. [[1934 in Romania|1934]])\n** [[Hubert Schoemaker]], Dutch-born American biochemist and executive (b. [[1950 in the Netherlands|1950]])\n* [[January 6]] \n** [[Lou Rawls]], African-American singer, songwriter and actor (b. [[1933 in the United States|1933]])\n** [[Hugh Thompson, Jr.]], soldier and pilot (b. [[1943 in the United States|1943]])\n* [[January 8]] \u2013 [[David Rosenbaum (journalist)|David Rosenbaum]]