4 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n** [[Pepsico]] announces its purchase of Star Foods for an undisclosed price saying that the purchase would strengthen its place as [[Poland]]'s number one seller of [[potato chip]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/03/business/03pepsi.html?scp=10&sq=&st=nyt|title=PepsiCo Buys Star Foods|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 3, 2006 | work=The New York Times| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225741/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/03/business/03pepsi.html?scp=10&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 3]] &ndash; Twelve dead coal miners and one survivor are discovered in the [[Sago Mine disaster|Sago Mine Disaster]] near [[Buckhannon, West Virginia]].\n* [[January 5]]\n** The [[Presidency of George W. Bush|Bush administration]] proposes spending [[United States dollar|$]]114 million on educational programs to expand the teaching of [[Arabic]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[Persian language|Persian]] and other languages typically not taught in public schools.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/06/politics/06language.html?scp=1&sq=&st=nyt|title=Bush Proposes Broader Language Training|work=The New York Times|date=January 6, 2006|accessdate=2009-03-20 | first=Michael | last=Janofsky| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225914/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/06/politics/06language.html?scp=1&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n** [[IBM]] says that it would freeze pension benefits for its American employees starting in 2008 and offer them only a [[401k]] retirement plan in future.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/06/business/06pension.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt|title=I.B.M. to Freeze Pension Plans to Trim Costs|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 6, 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225836/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/06/business/06pension.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 6]]\n** [[AOL]] agrees to pay customers as much as [[United States dollar|$]]25 million to settle claims that it wrongly billed them for some online services and products.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/07/technology/07aol.html?scp=10&sq=&st=nyt|title=AOL to Settle Billing Complaints|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 7, 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225944/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/07/technology/07aol.html?scp=10&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n** [[NYSE]] says that it has picked [[Bear Wagner]] as the firm that will handle trading of its shares when it goes public.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/07/business/07firm.html?scp=8&sq=&st=nyt|title=Big Board Selects Trader for Its Shares|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 7, 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424230020/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/07/business/07firm.html?scp=8&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 7]] &ndash; Embroiled in multiple scandals, former U.S. [[House Majority Leader]] [[Tom DeLay]] announces he will not seek to reassume his former post.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/01/07/AR2006010700831_pf.html|title=After Tom DeLay|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2006-02-08|accessdate=2009-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/delay-drops-bid-to-return-as-majority-leader|title=DeLay steps down as majority leader|publisher=[[MarketWatch]]|last=Watts|first= William L.|author2=Gelsi, Steve|date=2006-01-07|accessdate=2009-07-05}}</ref>\n* [[January 9]]\n**[[Vice President of the United States|Vice President]] [[Dick Cheney]] complains of [[shortness of breath]] and is treated at the hospital. The [[White House]] says the trip was necessary because of fluid retention as a [[adverse effect|side effect]] of a drug Mr. Cheney had taken to treat chronic foot ailments.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/10/politics/10cheney.html?scp=10&sq=&st=nyt|title=Cheney Makes a Morning Trip to the Hospital|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 10, 2006 | first1=David E. | last1=Sanger | first2=Lawrence K. | last2=Altman| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225951/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/10/politics/10cheney.html?scp=10&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n** The [[Dow Jones Industrial Average]] closes above 11,000 (11,011.90) for the first time since June 7, 2001.\n* [[January 10]] &ndash; [[Governor of California|Governor]] [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] proposes a [[United States dollar|$]]125.6 billion budget increasing spending without raising taxes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/11/national/11arnold.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt|title=Schwarzenegger Budget Calls for Billions in New Spending|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 11, 2006 | first=John M. | last=Broder| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225849/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/11/national/11arnold.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 11]] &ndash; The [[Augustine Volcano]] in [[Alaska]] erupts twice, marking its first major eruption since 1986.\n* [[January 13]]\n** The [[US Government]] reports that [[wholesale price index|wholesale]] inflation in 2005 increased by highest amount since 1990.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/14/business/14econ.html?scp=9&sq=&st=nyt|title=Wholesale Inflation Increases by Highest Amount Since 1990|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 14, 2006| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225936/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/14/business/14econ.html?scp=9&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-sta