's Operating Chief Steps Down; 2 Directors Are Named|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 19, 2006}}</ref>\n* [[January 19]] &ndash; [[NASA]] launches the ''[[New Horizons]]'' spacecraft in a 9-year, 3 billion mile space mission, to flyby and observe the dwarf planetary system of [[Pluto]]/[[Charon (moon)|Charon]] and possibly other [[Kuiper belt objects]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/20/science/space/20pluto.html?scp=8&sq=&st=nyt|title=NASA Launches Spacecraft on the First Mission to Pluto|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 20, 2006 | first=Warren E. | last=Leary| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424230028/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/20/science/space/20pluto.html?scp=8&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 20]] &ndash; A [[Maryland]] judge strikes down a state law banning [[same-sex marriage]] saying the measure violated a state constitutional amendment prohibiting sex discrimination.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/21/national/21marriage.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt|title=Maryland Judge Voids Ban on Same-Sex Marriage; State Quickly Appeals|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 21, 2006 | first=Adam | last=Liptak| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424230038/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/21/national/21marriage.html?scp=7&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 26]] &ndash; [[General Motors]] reports an [[United States dollar|$]]8.6 billion loss for 2005, its biggest loss since 1992.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/27/business/27auto.html?scp=11&sq=&st=nyt|title=G.M. Posts Worst Loss Since 1992|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 27, 2006 | first=Micheline | last=Maynard| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225828/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/27/business/27auto.html?scp=11&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 27]] &ndash; An inhaled form of [[insulin]] wins federal approval offering an alternative to [[Injection (medicine)|injection]]s for millions of people with [[diabetes]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/28/health/28diabetes.html?scp=4&sq=&st=nyt|title=U.S. Regulators Approve Insulin in Inhaled Form|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-20|date=January 28, 2006 | first1=Andrew | last1=Pollack | first2=Alex | last2=Berenson| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090424225841/http://www.nytimes.com/2006/01/28/health/28diabetes.html?scp=4&sq=&st=nyt| archivedate= 24 April 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n* [[January 30]]\n**The [[White House]] announces that [[President of the United States|President]] [[George W. Bush|Bush]] has chosen Professor [[Edward Lazear]], a [[Stanford University]] business professor to succeed [[Ben Bernanke]] as chairman of his [[Council of Economic Advisors]] who will succeed [[Alan Greenspan]] as Chairman of the [[Federal Reserve]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E06E4D81E3FF932A05752C0A9609C8B63&scp=15&sq=&st=nyt|title=White House Aide Picked|work=The New York Times|accessdate=2009-03-21|date=January 31, 2006}}</ref>\n** [[Jennifer San Marco]] kills eight people before committing suicide at a postal facility in [[Goleta, California]]. San Marco had worked at the facility previously, but had been let go due to her erratic behavior.\n* [[January 31]]\n** [[Samuel Alito]] is sworn in as an associate justice of the [[Supreme Court of the United States]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,183442,00.html|title=The Confirmation of Samuel Alito to the Supreme Court|publisher=[[Fox Broadcasting Company]]|date=2006-02-01|accessdate=2009-07-06|first=Bill|last=O'Reilly}}</ref>\n** Two [[federal appeals court]]s uphold rulings that the [[Partial Birth Abortion Act]] passed by the [[United States Congress]] in 2003 is 